{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}
In philosophy, the '''Cartesian Self''', part of a [[thought experiment]], is an individual's mind, separate from the body and the outside world, thinking about itself and its existence. It is distinguished from the [[Cartesian Other]], anything other than the Cartesian self. According to the philosopher [[Descartes]], there is a divide intrinsic to [[consciousness]], such that one cannot ever bridge the space between one's own consciousness and that of another.
Descartes concluded famously that [[Cogito ergo sum]], "I think, therefore I am", but realized that according to his [[wax argument]] you could never similarly demonstrate the existence of the 'other'. However, the Cartesian Self, he concluded, is thus almost entirely [[Self-evidence|self-evident]]: the existence of some being ''asking'' about itself necessarily implied that such a being existed. Because of this, while humans can know everything of the self and its mysteries, we cannot actually know anything of anything that is not the self.
It is based on the whole of the Cartesian Pure Inquirer, where cognitive capabilities and methods of achieving knowledge are alike to all knowers. However, the "knower" (particularly to Descartes) is treated as a featureless abstract, and not an actual person.
